without giving a lot away--

00:40:40.150 --> 00:40:43.120
the book has a long relationship
and a shorter relationship,

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:45.700
and the longer relationship
is a richer one

00:40:45.700 --> 00:40:47.340
and also gets more
time in the book.

00:40:47.340 --> 00:40:49.470
And was that intentional,
in terms of time,

00:40:49.470 --> 00:40:52.090
as well as how you
perceived the relationship?

00:40:52.090 --> 00:40:53.749
Is that a fair restatement?

00:40:53.749 --> 00:40:54.540
ADELLE WALDMAN: OK.

00:40:54.540 --> 00:40:55.921
I think this is
a great question.

00:40:55.921 --> 00:40:57.420
It's only tricky
for me to answer it

00:40:57.420 --> 00:40:59.552
in a way that is
meaningful to those

00:40:59.552 --> 00:41:01.760
who have read the book,
without giving too much away.

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:04.510
I'm going to try to do my best.

00:41:04.510 --> 00:41:08.320
So when I conceived the book,
I knew from the very beginning

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:10.540
who Nate was going
to end up with.

00:41:10.540 --> 00:41:17.720
And I wanted it to be not
obvious to readers, any more

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:21.520
than it was obvious to Nate.

00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:26.700
And there's a basic
little plot I had in mind,

00:41:26.700 --> 00:41:29.550
that I felt that, if I
could take-- I thought,

00:41:29.550 --> 00:41:31.880
there's this thing that
happens, sometimes,

00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:35.310
where-- this is from a
woman's perspective--

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:37.820
a woman in a heterosexual
relationship.

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:41.950
She's dating a guy, things
are good, for a while.

00:41:41.950 --> 00:41:44.180
Then things are less good.

00:41:44.180 --> 00:41:45.350
He seems to be pulling away.

00:41:45.350 --> 00:41:47.460
She doesn't know why.

00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:50.160
Things get worse and worse.

00:41:50.160 --> 00:41:52.720
And then, they finally break up.

00:41:52.720 --> 00:41:55.230
She is unhappy,
because she liked him.

00:41:55.230 --> 00:41:58.480
But she tells herself that,
well, this guy, really,

00:41:58.480 --> 00:41:59.550
has commitment issues.

00:41:59.550 --> 00:42:01.286
So that's clearly the problem.

00:42:01.286 --> 00:42:03.160
But then what happens--
like, a month later--

00:42:03.160 --> 00:42:08.310
he's suddenly moving in with
someone else who seems, maybe,

00:42:08.310 --> 00:42:10.440
less good for him, on paper.

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:12.250
And I thought-- I
felt like this was

00:42:12.250 --> 00:42:14.660
a scenario that
seemed just common.

00:42:14.660 --> 00:42:16.834
And I had heard of
it from friends.

00:42:16.834 --> 00:42:18.750
So I thought, wouldn't
it be neat to dramatize

00:42:18.750 --> 00:42:21.570
it-- to dramatize all
the players in it,

00:42:21.570 --> 00:42:23.160
and to be fair to each of them?

00:42:26.690 --> 00:42:29.102
So that played a role in
how I conceived the book.

00:42:29.102 --> 00:42:29.810
So in some ways--

00:42:29.810 --> 00:42:30.490
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON:
Because those things

00:42:30.490 --> 00:42:32.160
happen quickly, those--

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:33.150
ADELLE WALDMAN: Right.

00:42:33.150 --> 00:42:35.530
Like, the final relationship
happens quickly.

00:42:35.530 --> 00:42:39.160
It takes a long time for, maybe,
a bad relationship to play out,

00:42:39.160 --> 00:42:44.600
and a new relationship,
in this case,

00:42:44.600 --> 00:42:47.080
seemed to happen more quickly.

00:42:47.080 --> 00:42:51.055
So that's part of how I
saw the book's structure.

00:42:51.055 --> 00:42:54.054
I also thought, after
spending so much time

00:42:54.054 --> 00:42:55.470
on one relationship,
that I really

00:42:55.470 --> 00:42:57.310
wanted to trace
this whole arc, it

00:42:57.310 --> 00:42:59.780
would be tiresome
to do it again.

00:43:02.462 --> 00:43:05.440
I think those are the-- that
might be the best I can do,

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:06.660
without giving too much away.

00:43:06.660 --> 00:43:08.035
But I think it's
a good question,

00:43:08.035 --> 00:43:13.820
because it's an odd
choi-- and it's-- people--

00:43:13.820 --> 00:43:16.140
I do think the final chapter
does seem to come rather

00:43:16.140 --> 00:43:17.855
quickly.

00:43:17.855 --> 00:43:19.730
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON:
You've got a question?

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:22.271
AUDIENCE: I'm curious about your
overall process [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:34.777 --> 00:43:36.360
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON:
So the question

00:43:36.360 --> 00:43:39.270
was the process-- was there an
outline or a structure in mind?

00:43:39.270 --> 00:43:40.570
Was it iterative?

00:43:40.570 --> 00:43:41.630
What did you start with?

00:43:41.630 --> 00:43:42.680
ADELLE WALDMAN: Right.

00:43:42.680 --> 00:43:47.080
Well, I had this basic
arc, that I just described,

00:43:47.080 --> 00:43:49.210
of the relationship--
from beginning

00:43:49.210 --> 00:43:51.470
to end-- that I wanted to show.

00:43:51.470 --> 00:43:52.980
So I went with that.

00:43:52.980 --> 00:43:54.690
And I did know, from
the very beginning,

00:43:54.690 --> 00:43:57.480
who Nate was going
to end up with.

00:43:57.480 --> 00:44:01.180
And so I put that chara--
well, sort of put her in,

00:44:01.180 --> 00:44:03.660
early in the book, in
the way that I-- there's

00:44:03.660 --> 00:44:06.570
this saying among
writers of-- it's

00:44:06.570 --> 00:44:08.590
from Chekov, that
Chekov said, if there's

00:44:08.590 --> 00:44:12.480
a gun in the first act, it has
to go off in the third act.

00:44:12.480 --> 00:44:14.960
So I really wanted the
one Nate winds up with

00:44:14.960 --> 00:44:16.650
to be there from the
beginning, but not

00:44:16.650 --> 00:44:20.430
necessarily in a way you pay
attention to, at the time.

00:44:20.430 --> 00:44:23.140
So in that sense, I was very
much aware of the structure,

00:44:23.140 --> 00:44:24.120
from the beginning.

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:25.536
But that said,
that makes it sound

00:44:25.536 --> 00:44:28.024
like I had so much more control
or knew what I was doing.

00:44:28.024 --> 00:44:30.190
It took me so many years
to write this book, in part

00:44:30.190 --> 00:44:32.830
because I had to go back
and play with the structure.

00:44:32.830 --> 00:44:35.900
To try to get a relationship
in a slow decline,

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:38.660
the way Nate and
Hannah's eventually is,

00:44:38.660 --> 00:44:39.626
was so hard for me.

00:44:39.626 --> 00:44:42.000
I feel like it's something
we've all experienced-- again,

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.560
men or women, in real life.

00:44:44.560 --> 00:44:47.620
But it's hard to
dramatize relationships

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:50.804
just getting slightly
worse, because, you know,

00:44:50.804 --> 00:44:51.470
nothing happens.

00:44:51.470 --> 00:44:53.770
There's no-- no
one cheats, there's

00:44:53.770 --> 00:44:57.590
no violent fights,
where dishes are thrown.

00:44:57.590 --> 00:44:59.940
It's sort of a series of
dinners that are a little bit--

00:44:59.940 --> 00:45:01.815
something is off, and
they're kind of boring.

00:45:01.815 --> 00:45:04.064
It was, like, how do I write
about this without making

00:45:04.064 --> 00:45:07.060
the reader feel as bored as Nate
and Hannah do in the moment?

00:45:07.060 --> 00:45:08.780
And to sort of get
that right, and try

00:45:08.780 --> 00:45:13.310
to come up with scenes that
convey what's going on,

00:45:13.310 --> 00:45:17.170
without being terribly
boring, was really tricky.

00:45:17.170 --> 00:45:19.420
So it's like, I had
this overall structure,

00:45:19.420 --> 00:45:22.532
but the microscenes
took me a long time.

00:45:22.532 --> 00:45:23.740
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON: Great.

00:45:23.740 --> 00:45:24.730
Any other questions?

00:45:24.730 --> 00:45:26.330
Back here?

00:45:26.330 --> 00:45:27.205
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:30.255 --> 00:45:31.046
ADELLE WALDMAN: Oh!

00:45:31.046 --> 00:45:32.692
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:32.692 --> 00:45:33.775
ADELLE WALDMAN: Thank you.

00:45:33.775 --> 00:45:34.650
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:38.433 --> 00:45:39.880
ADELLE WALDMAN: Oh, thank you!

00:45:39.880 --> 00:45:40.755
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:52.271 --> 00:45:54.770
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON: So the
first was a lovely compliment,

00:45:54.770 --> 00:45:58.140
that this book is
recommended by our questioner

00:45:58.140 --> 00:45:59.280
to his male friends.

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:02.670
And the other is-- so,
if you're not aware,

00:46:02.670 --> 00:46:05.672
Adelle recently wrote-- is
"novella" the right word--?

00:46:05.672 --> 00:46:06.505
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:46:06.505 --> 00:46:06.850
ADELLE WALDMAN: I don't know.

00:46:06.850 --> 00:46:06.920
It's--

00:46:06.920 --> 00:46:07.320
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON:
A short story?

00:46:07.320 --> 00:46:10.600
ADELLE WALDMAN: --a long short
story, or a short novella.

00:46:10.600 --> 00:46:11.230
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON:
--called "New Year,"

00:46:11.230 --> 00:46:13.855
from the perspective one of the
female characters of the book--

00:46:13.855 --> 00:46:15.965
one of the friends
of Nate, who's

00:46:15.965 --> 00:46:18.020
a woman who is a
fascinating character,

00:46:18.020 --> 00:46:19.450
actually, in the book.

00:46:19.450 --> 00:46:22.240
And why did that
happen, or how did

00:46:22.240 --> 00:46:24.630
that come about--
kind of question.

00:46:24.630 --> 00:46:27.320
ADELLE WALDMAN: Yeah,
so-- it's so interesting.

00:46:27.320 --> 00:46:31.070
I didn't intend to write
this other short story, "New

00:46:31.070 --> 00:46:32.370
Year's," exactly.

00:46:32.370 --> 00:46:37.430
I had mentioned,
casually, to my publisher,

00:46:37.430 --> 00:46:39.570
that I had a lot
more material on each

00:46:39.570 --> 00:46:41.807
of the characters
in my book than,

00:46:41.807 --> 00:46:43.140
actually, make it into the book.

00:46:43.140 --> 00:46:44.181
Which is normal, I think.

00:46:44.181 --> 00:46:45.700
As a writer, you
spend so many years

00:46:45.700 --> 00:46:46.400
thinking about these characters.

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:49.200
So I knew-- you know, it
was fun for me to flesh out

00:46:49.200 --> 00:46:50.770
the backstory of
all the characters,

00:46:50.770 --> 00:46:53.350
even though it's not,
actually, in the book.

00:46:53.350 --> 00:46:58.230
And the publisher-- the guy
whose title is, literally,

00:46:58.230 --> 00:47:02.019
the publisher-- said, you know,
that might be fascinating.

00:47:02.019 --> 00:47:04.310
Would you be interested in
taking some of this material

00:47:04.310 --> 00:47:07.130
and putting it into a story?

00:47:07.130 --> 00:47:08.755
And I said, no.

00:47:08.755 --> 00:47:10.120
(LAUGHING) Absolutely not.

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:13.030
Because I thought the book
was an aesthetic whole.

00:47:13.030 --> 00:47:16.040
It was very important to me
to keep it in its perspective.

00:47:16.040 --> 00:47:19.415
I worried that another
perspective-- there

00:47:19.415 --> 00:47:23.820
would be a temptation for
me to moralize too much.

00:47:23.820 --> 00:47:25.320
I worried about all
sorts of things.

00:47:25.320 --> 00:47:30.740
At the same time, as soon as
he had raised this possibility,

00:47:30.740 --> 00:47:33.680
some part of my mind was a
little excited and intrigued

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:36.430
by it, because I really
loved writing this book,

00:47:36.430 --> 00:47:38.490
and I loved thinking
about all the characters.

00:47:38.490 --> 00:47:40.370
So it was a little
bit like an invitation

00:47:40.370 --> 00:47:43.750
to go back to a world that
I'd had a lot of fun in.

00:47:43.750 --> 00:47:46.660
And in the end, I was persuaded
to just give it a try.

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:48.200
And I said, OK, OK, I'll try it.

00:47:48.200 --> 00:47:49.908
But I'm not going to
guarantee that we're

00:47:49.908 --> 00:47:52.890
going to publish anything,
because I did have concerns.

00:47:52.890 --> 00:47:54.990
And I wound up writing
from the perspective

00:47:54.990 --> 00:47:58.315
of a character named
Aurit, who is sort

00:47:58.315 --> 00:48:01.440
of a truth-telling
female friend of Nate.

00:48:01.440 --> 00:48:05.280
She gives him a hard time about
the way he behaves with women.

00:48:05.280 --> 00:48:08.630
And she was a very fun
character to write.

00:48:08.630 --> 00:48:14.020
And it seemed fun to
inhabit her mindset.

00:48:14.020 --> 00:48:15.150
And it was fun.

00:48:15.150 --> 00:48:16.760
And I have to say, when I
sat down to write this story,

00:48:16.760 --> 00:48:17.968
it took on a life of its own.

00:48:17.968 --> 00:48:20.180
It wasn't something I
had thought I would do

00:48:20.180 --> 00:48:22.990
or intended to do, but
once I started doing it,

00:48:22.990 --> 00:48:24.690
I became invested in it.

00:48:24.690 --> 00:48:28.410
But I still feel a little--
it's hard for me to explain it,

00:48:28.410 --> 00:48:31.310
because it wasn't something
I ever thought I would do,

00:48:31.310 --> 00:48:33.110
and yet, I really enjoyed it.

00:48:33.110 --> 00:48:34.952
And I came to care
about the story.

00:48:34.952 --> 00:48:36.160
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON: Right.

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:37.470
Any final last question?

00:48:37.470 --> 00:48:38.747
We're almost out of time.

00:48:38.747 --> 00:48:39.580
You have a question?

00:48:39.580 --> 00:48:39.940
AUDIENCE: Uh-huh.

00:48:39.940 --> 00:48:40.620
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON:
All right; great.

00:48:40.620 --> 00:48:42.579
AUDIENCE: How did you
meet your literary agent?

00:48:42.579 --> 00:48:43.661
ADELLE WALDMAN: Oh, great!

00:48:43.661 --> 00:48:44.610
A practical question.

00:48:44.610 --> 00:48:47.926
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON: How
did you meet the agent?

00:48:47.926 --> 00:48:50.550
ADELLE WALDMAN: Well, when I had
written that first novel, that

00:48:50.550 --> 00:48:52.383
didn't get published,
I didn't know anything

00:48:52.383 --> 00:48:53.300
about book publishing.

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:54.716
It's funny; you
would have thought

00:48:54.716 --> 00:48:57.100
that-- I lived in New York,
and I worked in newspapers--

00:48:57.100 --> 00:48:58.099
that I would know a lot.

00:48:58.099 --> 00:49:00.910
But there's, actually,
a pretty strict divide

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:03.440
between people in
the newspaper world

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:06.185
and in the publishing world.

00:49:06.185 --> 00:49:08.810
And that's probably, too, why I
had these delusions of grandeur

00:49:08.810 --> 00:49:10.740
about what was going to happen.

00:49:10.740 --> 00:49:17.340
But at that point, I wrote
letters to literary agents

00:49:17.340 --> 00:49:20.872
that I saw in directories
of literary agents.

00:49:20.872 --> 00:49:21.580
You can buy them.

00:49:21.580 --> 00:49:22.910
Now they're mostly online.

00:49:22.910 --> 00:49:26.990
And you can also read the
acknowledgement pages of books,

00:49:26.990 --> 00:49:29.760
to see who the author's
literary agent is.

00:49:29.760 --> 00:49:32.130
I basically wrote--
I actually wrote

00:49:32.130 --> 00:49:33.480
letters, when I think about it.

00:49:33.480 --> 00:49:34.960
Some were paper letters.

00:49:34.960 --> 00:49:37.500
There were some that were
email, but-- it was so long ago.

00:49:40.270 --> 00:49:41.930
And that worked.

00:49:41.930 --> 00:49:42.940
I got some responses.

00:49:42.940 --> 00:49:44.470
People asked to see it.

00:49:44.470 --> 00:49:49.676
But then many of them said
no to that particular book.

00:49:49.676 --> 00:49:53.339
But by the time I wrote
this novel, one of my goals,

00:49:53.339 --> 00:49:55.880
while writing it, was also to
learn more about the publishing

00:49:55.880 --> 00:49:57.220
world, to be in
a better position

00:49:57.220 --> 00:49:58.610
by the time I
finished the novel.

00:49:58.610 --> 00:50:02.880
So I had tried to make an
effort to write book reviews

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:04.650
and get to know
people who were more

00:50:04.650 --> 00:50:06.890
connected to the literary
world and publishing,

00:50:06.890 --> 00:50:09.760
and to meet more
authors of books.

00:50:09.760 --> 00:50:10.700
And that helped a lot.

00:50:10.700 --> 00:50:14.520
Because this time,
when I wrote to agents,

00:50:14.520 --> 00:50:15.530
I did do the same thing.

00:50:15.530 --> 00:50:20.690
I sort of asked around, to find
out who some good agents were.

00:50:20.690 --> 00:50:21.760
And I wrote emails.

00:50:21.760 --> 00:50:25.360
But this time, I tended
to write emails that said,

00:50:25.360 --> 00:50:27.510
my friend so-and-so,
who's one of your clients,

00:50:27.510 --> 00:50:29.310
suggested I contact you .

00:50:29.310 --> 00:50:32.930
And that, I have to
admit, helped a lot.

00:50:32.930 --> 00:50:35.780
On the other hand, I did get
responses, even the first time.

00:50:35.780 --> 00:50:38.940
I mean, I do think my first
novel was rejected because

00:50:38.940 --> 00:50:41.090
of the contents, not because
I didn't know people.

00:50:41.090 --> 00:50:44.950
But I do think-- if
anyone here is thinking

00:50:44.950 --> 00:50:48.490
about these things-- I think
that it is, probably, true

00:50:48.490 --> 00:50:52.660
that it can be helpful to
get a quicker response,

00:50:52.660 --> 00:50:54.040
if you have some connection.

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:55.664
And that's unfortunate.

00:50:55.664 --> 00:50:57.580
I mean, one shouldn't
have to live in New York

00:50:57.580 --> 00:51:01.270
and hang out with writers
to get a quick response

00:51:01.270 --> 00:51:04.302
from a literary
agent, but so it is.

00:51:04.302 --> 00:51:06.760
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON: That's
true in many businesses, yes?

00:51:06.760 --> 00:51:07.780
I see some nods in the room.

00:51:07.780 --> 00:51:09.500
Well, thank you so
much, Adelle, and thanks

00:51:09.500 --> 00:51:11.000
to all of you for
coming, and anyone

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.599
who joined us on
the live stream.

00:51:13.599 --> 00:51:15.140
If you have not read
the book, I hope

00:51:15.140 --> 00:51:17.060
you want to to, after this talk.

00:51:17.060 --> 00:51:19.020
And, uh, have a great day.

00:51:19.020 --> 00:51:19.520
Thanks.

00:51:19.520 --> 00:51:20.120
ADELLE WALDMAN: Thanks, again.

00:51:20.120 --> 00:51:20.620
[APPLAUSE]

00:51:20.620 --> 00:51:22.820
Thanks so much for being here.

00:51:22.820 --> 00:51:24.370
CLAIRE HUGHES JOHNSON: Great.

